\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. R. rugosum} (L.) All., {\i  Fl. Pedem. }{\b 1}: 257 (1785). Annual 15-60(-100) cm, hispid below, often glabrous above. Lower leaves pinnate; upper usually dentate, sessile to petiolate. Petals 6-10 mm, pale yellow. Silicula 3-10 mm; upper segment 3-6 mm (including beak), ovoid to globose, abruptly contracted into a filiform beak 1-3(-5) mm; lower segment (0·7-)1·2-3 mm, cylindrical to ellipsoidal.{\i  S. Europe; naturalized or casual in much of C. & N. Europe.} Al Az Bl Bu Co Cr Ga Gr Hs It Ju Lu Rs(K, E) Sa Si Tu [Au Be Br Cz Ge Hb He Ho Hu Po Rm Rs(C, W)].
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 A variable species, with several variants treated at subspecific rank or as species. The following subspecies are more or less distinct, although intermediates occur.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b rugosum}: Pedicels 1·5-3·2 mm, thick (up to 1·3 mm in diameter). Lower segment of the fruit 1-1½ times as wide as the pedicel, obconical, not constricted above; upper segment obovoid, usually deeply ribbed and rugose. 2n = 16. {\i S. Europe; widely naturalized elsewhere}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp.{\b  orientale} (L.) Arcangeli, Comp. Fl. Ital. 49 (1882) ({\i R. orientale} (L.) Crantz; incl. {\i R. rugosum} subsp. {\i linnaeanum} Rouy & Fouc., {\i R. linnaeanum} Boiss. & Reuter, nom. illeg.,{\i  R. hispanicum} (L.) Crantz): Pedicels 2-3·5 mm, slender (up to 0·7 mm in diameter). Lower segment of the fruit 1½-2 times as wide as the pedicel, ellipsoidal, constricted above; upper segment broadly ellipsoidal, usually shallowly ribbed and slightly rugose.{\i  Mediterranean region; widely naturalized or casual elsewhere}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Plants of subsp. ({\b b}) with the lower segment of the fruit sterile, 0·7-1·2 mm, and less than 1½ times as wide as the pedicel, have been called subsp.{\b  linnaeanum} Rouy & Fouc.,{\i  Fl. Fr.}{\b  2}: 73 (1895), but the variation between them and subsp. ({\b b}) is continuous, and they probably do not merit formal taxonomic recognition. The lower segment of the fruit of subsp. ({\b a}) is usually fertile.
